Review: Wanted something good bad, but this was just bad bad.
It’s a great set-up for a movie, and for the most part it works. But there are a few goofy hiccups along the way, and the ending just feels…odd.
Doesn’t pack the same “WTF” energy as Tickled, but Mister Organ is well-made and intriguing (and genuinely insufferable, thanks to its namesake).
A tense and borderline suffocating first half unfortunately gives way to a slower, laborious second half, and concludes on a wholly unsatisfactory note.

My first dip into Christopher Lee’s early schlock horror films (via Severin’s Eurocrypt boxset) and it’s certainly an odd one. The story of a bunch of hedonistic criminals becoming trapped in a madman’s castle is interesting enough, but the script is so utterly devoid of scares, suspense, character development, or anything else you’d expect from a competent movie that it all falls flat. The film’s framing device - a blackmail scheme gone wrong - is equally head-scratching, to the point…

Movie: In the Heat of the Night
Roadrunner: A Film About Anthony Bourdain

Review: The overtly-dramatic music stings and slow zooms add a layer of kitsch to the story that I quite enjoyed, but despite this and some great performances (especially from Melton, who perfectly embodies Joe’s stunted development and stifled trauma), I couldn’t connect with the material beyond surface-level admiration that Haynes was able to pull this off.
A fun and creepy premise is consistently undermined by obnoxious characters (especially Lin Shaye’s) and an ending that wants its cake and eats it too.
It’s biggest sin is how utterly familiar and bland it is.

Review: The movie seems to think the audience needs to be convinced that Russ is a sociopath, and so spends most of the runtime relying on personal testimonies and showing the graphic footage from his many “haunts.” For a movie called “Monster Inside,” we learn incredibly little about the psychology of the man.
